    "code": "H81.10",
    "rawCode": "H8110",
    "shortDesc": "Benign paroxysmal vertigo, unspecified ear",
    "longDesc": "Benign paroxysmal vertigo, unspecified ear",
    "plainEnglish": "Benign paroxysmal vertigo is a condition where you suddenly experience severe spinning sensations (vertigo) that come and go in brief episodes, typically lasting seconds to minutes. This happens because of loose calcium carbonate crystals floating in the fluid of your inner ear, which interferes with your balance system. The spinning sensation can be intense and disorienting, but it's not dangerous and doesn't cause permanent damage to your hearing or balance.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, otolaryngologists (ear, nose, and throat specialists), and primary care physicians use this code when diagnosing patients with recurrent dizziness episodes. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing vestibular testing or seeking treatment for persistent vertigo, especially when the specific affected ear hasn't been determined.",
