    "code": "H93.19",
    "rawCode": "H9319",
    "shortDesc": "Tinnitus, unspecified ear",
    "longDesc": "Tinnitus, unspecified ear",
    "plainEnglish": "Tinnitus is a persistent ringing, buzzing, hissing, or roaring sound in the ear that only you can hear—it's not caused by an external sound. This condition can result from exposure to loud noise, ear infections, aging, or circulation problems, and it may be constant or come and go. While tinnitus itself isn't dangerous, it can be annoying or distressing, interfering with sleep or concentration.",
    "whoUses": "Audiologists, otolaryngologists (ENTs), and primary care physicians commonly use this code when evaluating patients with ear noise complaints. It frequently appears on patient EOB statements when tinnitus is diagnosed or treated, particularly during audiology visits or ENT consultations.",
